  "prompt": "What is the definition of potential energy?",
  "response": "Potential energy is defined as the energy stored in an object due to its position, configuration, or state. It is the energy that an object possesses because of its position relative to other objects, its condition, or its arrangement. The most common type of potential energy is gravitational potential energy, which depends on an object's height above the ground and its mass. Mathematically, gravitational potential energy (U) can be expressed as:\n\n\\[ U = mgh \\]\n\nwhere:\n- \\( U \\) is the gravitational potential energy,\n- \\( m \\) is the mass of the object,\n- \\( g \\) is the acceleration due to gravity, and\n- \\( h \\) is the height of the object above a reference point.\n\nOther forms of potential energy include elastic potential energy (stored in materials when they are stretched or compressed) and chemical potential energy (stored in the bonds of chemical compounds). The concept of potential energy is crucial in physics as it helps explain the behavior of objects in various forces and field interactions.",
